    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="686"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d686">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 825.6374/355</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chilean Chargé</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MVG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Munizaga Varela</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 891</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1918</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 29.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to note No. 81 of July 27, last, from
                    the Department of State relative to the favorable settlement of the difficulties
                        <pb facs="0810" n="718" xml:id="pg_718"/> arising from the embargo placed
                    upon certain petroleum stored in Iquique and Tocopilla,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d686fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_712">p. 712</ref>.</note> I
                    have the honor to inform Your Excellency that I transmitted its contents to my
                    Government and have received in reply the following telegram from the Minister
                    of Foreign Relations: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>There has been no judgment whatever against the Union Oil Co., nor any
                            embargo of that company’s petroleum, but only against the International
                            Petroleum Co., whose agents here are Williamson &amp; Co. [<hi
                                rend="italic">sic</hi>], and whose petroleum in the tanks at Iquique
                            and Tocopilla was embargoed. The embargo declared against Williamson
                            &amp; Co. in the action brought by Gildemeister, has been finally raised
                            by a judicial decree, and the Government has guaranteed that there shall
                            not be any embargo again declared.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I avail myself [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">G. Munizaga Varela</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
